GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 720
Short Title: Insurance Guaranty Association Act Revisions.-AB (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives Humphrey, Setzer, and Balkcom (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Insurance, if favorable, Finance, if favorable, Rules, Calendar, and Operations of
the House
April 3, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT ENACTING REVISIONS TO THE INSURANCE GUARANTY ASSOCIATION
3 ACT, AS RECOMMENDED BY THE DEPARTMENT OF INSURANCE.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5 SECTION 1. G.S. 58-48-10 reads as rewritten:
6 "§ 58-48-10. Scope.
7 This Article shall apply to all kinds of direct insurance, but shall not be applicable to:
8 …
9 (5) Insurance Other than coverages that may be set forth in a cybersecurity
10 insurance policy, insurance of warranties or service contracts;
11 …."
12 SECTION 2. G.S. 58-48-20 reads as rewritten:
13 "§ 58-48-20. Definitions.
14 As used in this Article:
15 …
16 (4) Covered claim. – An unpaid claim, including one of unearned premiums,
17 which is in excess of fifty dollars ($50.00) and arises out of and is within the
18 coverage and not in excess of the applicable limits of an insurance policy to
19 which this Article applies as issued by an insurer, if that insurer if the policy
20 was issued by an insurer that becomes an insolvent insurer after the effective
21 date of this Article and (i) the claimant or insured is a resident of this State at
22 the time of the insured event; or (ii) the property from which the claim arises
23 is permanently located in this State. "Covered claim" includes claim
24 obligations that arose through the issuance of an insurance policy by a member
25 insurer, which are later allocated, transferred, merged into, novated, assumed
26 by, or otherwise made the sole responsibility of a member or nonmember
27 insurer if (i) the original member insurer has no remaining obligations on the
28 policy after the transfer, (ii) a final order of liquidation with a finding of
29 insolvency has been entered against the insurer that assumed the member's
30 coverage obligations by a court of competent jurisdiction in the insurer's state
31 of domicile, (iii) the claim would have been a covered claim, as defined in this
32 subdivision, if the claim had remained the responsibility of the original
33 member insurer and the order of liquidation had been entered against the
34 original member insurer, with the same claim submission date and liquidation
*H720-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 date, and (iv) in cases where the member's coverage obligations were assumed
2 by a nonmember insurer, the transaction received prior regulatory or judicial
3 approval. "Covered claim" shall not include any amount awarded (i) as
4 punitive or exemplary damages; (ii) sought as a return of premium under any
5 retrospective rating plan; or (iii) due any reinsurer, insurer, insurance pool, or
6 underwriting association, as subrogation or contribution recoveries or
7 otherwise. "Covered claim" also shall not include fines or penalties, including
8 attorneys' fees, imposed against an insolvent insurer or its insured or claims
9 of any claimant whose net worth exceeds fifty million dollars ($50,000,000)
10 on December 31 of the year preceding the date the insurer becomes insolvent.
11 (4a) Cybersecurity insurance. – Includes first and third-party coverage, in a policy
12 or endorsement, written on a direct, admitted basis by a member insurer for
13 losses and loss mitigation arising out of or relating to data privacy breaches,
14 unauthorized information network security intrusions, computer viruses,
15 ransomware, cyber extortion, identity theft, and similar exposures.
16 …."
17 SECTION 3. G.S. 58-48-35 reads as rewritten:
18 "§ 58-48-35. Powers and duties of the Association.
19 (a) The Association shall:
20 (1) Be obligated to the extent of the covered claims existing prior to the
21 determination of insolvency and arising within 30 days after the determination
22 of insolvency, or before the policy expiration date if less than 30 days after
23 the determination, or before the insured replaces the policy or causes its
24 cancellation, if he does so within 30 days of the determination. This obligation
25 includes only the amount of each covered claim that is in excess of fifty dollars
26 ($50.00) and is less than five hundred thousand dollars ($500,000). However,
27 the Association shall pay the full amount of a covered claim for benefits under
28 a workers' compensation insurance coverage, and shall pay an amount not
29 exceeding ten thousand dollars ($10,000) per policy for a covered claim for
30 the return of unearned premium. In no event shall the Association be obligated
31 to pay an amount in excess of five hundred thousand dollars ($500,000) for
32 all first and third-party claims under a policy or endorsement providing, or
33 that is found to provide, cybersecurity insurance coverage and arising out of
34 or related to a single insured event, regardless of the number of claims made
35 or the number of claimants. The Association has no obligation to pay a
36 claimant's covered claim, except a claimant's workers' compensation claim, if:
37 …
38 (4) Investigate claims brought against the Association and adjust, compromise,
39 settle, and pay covered claims to the extent of the Association's obligation and
40 deny all other claims and may review settlements, releases and judgments to
41 which the insolvent insurer or its insureds were parties to determine the extent
42 to which such settlements, releases and judgments may be properly
43 contested.claims. This requirement is subject to the following provisions:
44 a. When investigating, adjusting, compromising, or settling claims, the
45 Association may appoint, substitute, and direct legal counsel for the
46 defense of covered claims and appoint and direct other service
47 providers for covered services.
48 b. The Association may pay in any order that it deems reasonable,
49 including the payment of claims as they are received from the
50 claimants or in groups or categories of claims.
51 …
Page 2 House Bill 720-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (8) Have the right to review and contest settlements, releases, compromises,
2 waivers, and judgments to which the insolvent insurer or its insureds were
3 parties prior to the entry of the order of liquidation. This right is subject to the
4 following provisions:
5 a. In addition to any defenses available to the insurer, the Association
6 may assert any statutory defenses or rights of offset against any
7 settlement, release, compromise, or waiver executed by an insured or
8 the insurer or any judgment taken against the insured or the insurer.
9 b. The Association is not bound by a settlement, release, compromise, or
10 waiver executed by an insured or the insurer or any judgment entered
11 against an insured or the insurer by consent or through a failure to
12 exhaust all appeals if the settlement, release, compromise, waiver, or
13 judgment was:
14 1. Executed or entered within 120 days prior to the entry of an
15 order of liquidation, and the insured or the insurer did not use
16 reasonable care in entering into the settlement, release,
17 compromise, waiver, or judgment, or did not pursue all
18 reasonable appeals of an adverse judgment; or
19 2. Executed by or taken against an insured or the insurer based on
20 default, fraud, collusion, or the insurer's failure to defend.
21 c. If a court of competent jurisdiction finds that the Association is not
22 bound by a settlement, release, compromise, waiver, or judgment for
23 any of the reasons described in sub-subdivision b. of this subdivision,
24 the settlement, release, compromise, waiver, or judgment shall be set
25 aside, and the Association shall be permitted to defend any covered
26 claim on the merits. The settlement, release, compromise, waiver, or
27 judgment may not be considered as evidence of liability or damages in
28 connection with any claim brought against the Association or any
29 other party under this Article.
30 d. Any covered claims arising from any judgment under any decision,
31 verdict, or finding based on the default of the insolvent insurer or its
32 failure to defend an insured shall, upon application and notice by the
33 Association, be vacated and set aside by the same court in which such
34 judgment, order, decision, verdict, or finding is entered, and the
35 Association either on its own behalf or on behalf of any insured or an
36 insolvent insurer shall be permitted to defend against such claim on
37 the merits. Any party who has obtained any such judgment or order
38 shall have the right, upon application and notice, to have the judgment
39 or order restored if within 90 days following the entry of the judgment
40 or order the Association has not notified such party and the court that
41 it intends to defend the matter on the merits.
42 …."
43 SECTION 4. G.S. 58-48-50 reads as rewritten:
44 "§ 58-48-50. Effect of paid claims.
45 …
46 (a1) The Association shall have the right to recover from the following persons the amount
47 of any "covered claim" paid and any and all expenses incurred, including attorneys' fees and costs
48 of defense, in connection with any claim against the person or the person's affiliate pursuant to
49 this Article:
50 (1) Any insured whose net worth on December 31 of the year next preceding the
51 date the insurer becomes insolvent exceeds fifty million dollars ($50,000,000)
House Bill 720-First Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 and whose liability obligations to other persons are satisfied in whole or in
2 part by payments under this Article; Article, provided that an insured's net
3 worth on that date shall be deemed to include the aggregate net worth of the
4 insured and all of its subsidiaries and affiliates as calculated on a consolidated
5 basis; or
6 …."
7 SECTION 5. G.S. 58-48-85 reads as rewritten:
8 "§ 58-48-85. Stay of proceedings; reopening of default judgments.proceedings.
9 All proceedings in which the insolvent insurer is a party or is obligated to defend a party in
10 any court or before any administrative agency or the North Carolina Industrial Commission shall
11 be stayed automatically for 120 days and such additional time thereafter as may be determined
12 by the court from the date the insolvency is determined or any ancillary proceedings are initiated
13 in this State, whichever is later, to permit proper defense by the Association of all pending causes
14 of action. Any party to any proceeding which is stayed pursuant to this section shall have the
15 right, upon application and notice, to seek a vacation or modification of such stay. Any covered
16 claims arising from any judgment under any decision, verdict or finding based on the default of
17 the insolvent insurer or its failure to defend an insured, shall, upon application and notice by the
18 Association be vacated and set aside by the same court in which such judgment, order, decision,
19 verdict, or finding is entered and the Association either on its own behalf or on behalf of any
20 insured or an insolvent insurer, shall be permitted to defend against such claim on the merits.
21 Any party who has obtained any such judgment or order shall have the right, upon application
22 and notice, to have the judgment or order restored if within 90 days following the entry of the
23 judgment or order the Association has not notified such party and the court that it intends to
24 defend the matter on the merits."
25 SECTION 6. This act is effective when it becomes law.
